cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this software, please cite it using the metadata from this file."
title: "embraOS-QNM-Core: identity as a conserved charge of the dynamics (a non-LLM core)"
abstract: >-
  embraOS-QNM-Core is a custom, non-LLM AI core in which a system's identity and
  "soul" are a conserved charge of the core's own dynamics — an Epoch Automaton
  E = (S, Σ, δ, s₀, F, ψ) whose invariant ψ is sealed at genesis and preserved by
  construction ("conservation beats checking"), rather than a rule checked at each
  step. It is the pivot target of the now-relic embraOS-QNM program, which
  established across two substrates and four pre-registered reader families that a
  frozen, web-trained LLM cannot host a readable identity invariant. This
  math-first snapshot provides a formal specification with one falsifiable theorem
  — a conserved-charge ψ survives the "replica test" (a survivor versus an
  identical copy) because the charge hides in the part of the state that the
  observable readout erases — together with a runnable, tested sandbox that
  demonstrates it (conserved-ψ replica AUC 1.000 vs an endpoint-only null of
  0.500). Phase two lifts the core to a learned identity-manifold and reports,
  honestly, that identity is reliably discriminable through the dynamics — which
  conservation law a trajectory obeys (discriminator AUC 1.0 across seeds) —
  precisely where static geometry is only seed-noise. Negative results are
  recorded rather than buried, in the project's pre-registration style. Developed
  by William Ward (Ward Software Defined Systems LLC) with Embra as co-investigator.
